{"timestamp":"2026-05-19T10:20:02.279Z","taskId":"KB-005","text":"` having been run first. This needs to be clear in the test setup. The spec does say \"After a successful `npm run build`, read and parse `dist/about/index.html`\" — but it doesn't specify whether the test file itself should run the build or assume it's already done. This is a gap. Looking more carefully, the spec says:\n   - \"Run `npm run build` — must succeed with exit code 0\"\n   - \"Run `npm run test` — all tests pass\"\n\n   But the tests read from `dist/about/index.html`. If `npm run test` is run independently of `npm run build`, the tests would fail. The spec needs to either:\n   a. Have the test file run the build first (e.g., in a beforeAll/b","type":"thinking","agent":"reviewer"}
{"timestamp":"2026-05-19T10:20:04.733Z","taskId":"KB-005","text":"eforeEach)\n   b. Or specify that `npm run build` must be run before `npm run test`\n   c. Or add a build step to the test setup\n\n   Actually, this is important. The test file reads from `dist/about/index.html` but doesn't trigger the build. The spec's step checklist says both `npm run build` and `npm run test` must succeed,","type":"thinking","agent":"reviewer"}
{"timestamp":"2026-05-19T10:20:06.697Z","taskId":"KB-005","text":" but they're separate commands. If someone runs just `npm run test`, it would fail unless `dist/` already exists from a previous build.\n\n   This is a notable gap but might be considered a minor issue since the spec explicitly says \"After a successful `npm run build`\" in the test file description. But in practice, the test should be robust enough to either build first or have a","type":"thinking","agent":"reviewer"}
