{"timestamp":"2026-05-19T12:16:46.597Z","taskId":"KB-005","text":" of a quote. The proper way would be to use `<figcaption>` with the source name not inside `<cite>`. However, using `<cite>` for source attribution is extremely common practice and is recommended by many accessibility guides. The spec does say it's for \"the title of a work,\" but practical usage often extends it to attribution. This is a very minor semantic quibble.\n\nActually, looking more","type":"thinking","agent":"reviewer"}
{"timestamp":"2026-05-19T12:16:48.934Z","taskId":"KB-005","text":" carefully at the HTML spec: `<cite>` is for \"the title of a work\" (like a book, article, etc.). For a publication name as a quote source, it's actually semantically appropriate since a publication name IS the title of a work. So this is fine.\n\n2. The `<blockquote>` element - should the text be in a `<p>` inside `<blockquote>`, or directly","type":"thinking","agent":"reviewer"}
